# Corrected Response

Intermittent fasting is one of several dietary patterns that may offer health benefits for some people. Research suggests it can support weight management and improve certain metabolic markers in appropriate individuals. However, the evidence does not show that it is the healthiest diet for everyone.

Whether intermittent fasting is suitable depends on many factors, including age, pregnancy, existing medical conditions, medications, nutritional needs, and personal preferences. Some people may benefit from it, while others may be advised to avoid it.

No major health organization recommends intermittent fasting as a universal treatment for all diseases or advises everyone to skip breakfast or eat only one meal a day. Individuals considering significant dietary changes should consult a qualified healthcare professional, especially if they have underlying health conditions.

